\addvspace {10\p@ }
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.1}{\ignorespaces Three-layer system architecture of the ADHD Second Brain. The User Layer comprises a SwiftUI menu bar application, a React dashboard, and a Telegram bot interface. The Backend Layer hosts the FastAPI server (\texttt {localhost:8420}) with its constituent modules (${\sim }500$\,MB RAM $+$ ${\sim }2.3$\,GB GPU). The Data Layer uses PostgreSQL with pgvector for persistent and vector-indexed storage. Dashed arrows indicate external service calls.}}{23}{figure.caption.12}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.2}{\ignorespaces Hot Path and Warm Path data flows. The Hot Path (solid arrows) processes screen monitoring events through activity classification, ADHD metrics computation, SetFit emotion prediction, and JITAI evaluation with confidence-gated emotion context within a 100\,ms budget. The Warm Path (dashed arrows) processes conversational input through a unified SenticNet analysis (safety, emotion, and ADHD signals concurrently), a safety gate, LLM context construction with memory retrieval, LLM generation, and memory storage within a 3\,s budget.}}{24}{figure.caption.13}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.3}{\ignorespaces Four-tier SenticNet orchestration pipeline. Each tier is evaluated sequentially; Tier~1 may short-circuit to an emergency pathway if safety thresholds are exceeded. All four tiers execute in full analysis mode; Tier~4 is skipped only in lightweight mode.}}{27}{figure.caption.15}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.4}{\ignorespaces Semantic memory retrieval pipeline. User input is encoded via OpenAI's \texttt {text-embedding-3-small} model, matched against the pgvector index by cosine similarity, and injected into the LLM prompt.}}{29}{figure.caption.17}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.5}{\ignorespaces Four-level hierarchical activity classifier. Each level is attempted in sequence; classification terminates at the first level that produces a confident result. Levels~1--3 are rule-based and resolve 78\% of events in under 5\,ms. Level~4 (embedding fallback) is invoked for the remaining 22\%.}}{30}{figure.caption.18}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.6}{\ignorespaces JITAI evaluation and personalisation loop. Real-time metrics and confidence-gated SetFit emotion context feed into the seven-rule executive function evaluation across four Barkley domains. When intervention is warranted, Thompson Sampling selects the intervention type, and user responses update the Beta distribution parameters for subsequent decisions.}}{32}{figure.caption.19}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.1}{\ignorespaces SetFit-inspired contrastive learning pipeline for emotion classification. Phase 1 fine-tunes the sentence encoder using exhaustive pair generation and CoSENTLoss. Phase 2 classifies new input using the fine-tuned encoder and a logistic regression head.}}{41}{figure.caption.23}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.1}{\ignorespaces Confusion matrix for the production SetFit emotion classifier evaluated on 50 held-out test sentences (43 correct, 86\% accuracy). Diagonal entries indicate correct classifications; off-diagonal entries indicate misclassifications. The primary confusion axis lies in the anxious category, which is misclassified across frustrated, disengaged, and overwhelmed.}}{53}{figure.caption.29}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.2}{\ignorespaces Pipeline latency waterfall showing the percentage contribution of each component to the total end-to-end latency of 13,961~ms. Mem0 store dominates at 38.8\% and is amenable to asynchronous execution.}}{58}{figure.caption.33}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.3}{\ignorespaces Energy breakdown per pipeline execution by hardware component. GPU computation dominates at 71.8\%, reflecting the matrix multiplication-intensive nature of LLM inference on Apple Silicon.}}{59}{figure.caption.35}%
